article.description: Despite 20 turnovers, the host Detroit Shock did enough things right to beat the slumping Charlotte Sting, 69-55 Friday night.
article.headline: Detroit overcomes 20 turnovers to win
article.linkText: Shock bounce back to ward off Sting
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Despite 20 turnovers, the Detroit
Shock did enough things right to beat the slumping Charlotte Sting.

After dropping their first game of the season Wednesday to
Seattle, the Shock cruised to a 69-55 victory over the Sting on
Friday night.

"You could see that we were finally ready to play again,"
Detroit coach Bill Laimbeer said. "We still made some dumb
turnovers, but you can't fault our effort this time."

Elaine Powell and Cheryl Ford scored 12 points each to lead the
Shock, who jumped out to an early 23-7 lead. With All-Star Swin
Cash still recovering from a knee injury and Deanna Nolan having a
rare off-night with just nine points, the Shock used balanced
scoring to get the win.

"It was important to get everyone involved tonight," Powell
said. "We came out aggressive and picked up our intensity."

Sheri Sam and Teana McKiver led the Sting with eight points
each. Charlotte (1-6) lost its third in a row and are last in the
league in scoring, falling short of their 61.8 average.

"I think we have problems putting the ball in the hole," Sting
guard Dawn Staley said. "On the road and at home, we have trouble
scoring. We've got to figure it out pretty quickly."

Ayana Walker and Chandi Jones added 10 points apiece for
Detroit, which shot 55 percent from the field. Ford went 5-for-9
and had 10 rebounds. The Shock outrebounded the Sting 31-23.

"We were just up against a better team," Charlotte coach Trudi
Lacey said. "We missed shots and didn't convert turnovers into
points."

Detroit led by as many as 16 in the first half, but Charlotte
narrowed the margin to 32-28 at the break with the help of 11 Shock
turnovers.

The Shock moved the lead to double digits early in the second
half, but missed nine of their first 17 free-throw attempts.
Detroit took a 61-45 lead, holding Charlotte without a field goal
for over 5 minutes, to put the game out of reach.

The Sting, who shot 33 percent, have lost five straight to
Detroit.
